spacekadt

Welcome to the 16th iteration of this thread! Ask your simpler game questions here, and see them answered (usually!)

We use a particular format, so please be sure to number your questions and answers accordingly. Also, please attempt to search the forum before you ask; the answer may have been posted in a previous thread. You can also refer to Mushpedia.

For those replying to questions, try to give accurate answers and to check your answer before replying if you're not sure.

Please note that this thread is not meant for questions leading to possible debates, to complex advice, or questions about the SDF.

Format Example:

Person with a questionQ1: If the ship moves, and we don't arrive at a planet, what happens to the planets we scanned?

(Person with an answer) A1: Those planets are lost forever, and you have to scan for new ones.

Before you post, consider this:

You probably shouldn't reveal too many details about your ship in your question. If your character isn't an important part of your question, leave your identity out. Whether you're Mush should also be left out, unless the question directly relates to Mush activity.

If people need more details in order to answer your question, they'll ask for them.

We've seen FAR too many newbies post things like, "I'm so and so and Mush, and this is what's going on on my ship." before asking a question...without realizing that experienced people not only read the forum, they might also read that very question, and might be on your ship. That usually ends badly for the person asking the question.

[8744424]

And that's why it's a good practice for launching pilots to check in rooms logs if enough people (and especially diplomat) have grabbed the spacesuits.

spacekadt
Soroosh

Q20 : Is it possible to spot a mush by Ctrl + W ? Like when It says this skills would be lost when mush, that means this guy is mush?

This

That coffee junkie is unique you know, I never seen it shows like that, even in past games using this thing

To add a bit of detail, both Ctrl+W and AstroPad are completely mush-proofed. They cannot give away a mush in any way.

In the case of Ctrl+W, it simply shows what skills wouldn't work if mush (and is like that with *every* skill that wouldn't work as mush, regardless of current mush/humanity status).

AstroPad and food/med properties are only updated if somoene with the appropriate skill has already put those properties into AstroPad. Just because Janice updated the fruit and it shows properties (for instance), that doesn't mean she's mush, just that a botanist previously updated that info.

Q29: how does guarding the FC work if there is already a person inside the room (that mostly came from CC)?? will he be able to pick items and leave anywhere or pick items and move to CC only....
Another one.. do others can pick items while there is guard active in the room?

On may 23, 2017
[8191292]

A29

If You guard room in which somebody already is present, than said person can go only into a room from which he originally camed back. Simple example: Ian moved from Lab to FC. Chun comes into FC some time later and starts guarding it. Ian comes online and his only option to move is to move back into Lab.

As for picking an items - guarding rooms does not protect items from being picked up in any way. So answer to that is YES. Everybody can enter guarded room, pick whatever items are there (search for them if needed!) and go back from where they camed.

TeufelsAdvokat

Shooter is just free points and don't really come into the equation.

Gunner is way better at taking out the small waves as Pilots need 4 AP to take off and land, which equals 2-3 hits from a Gunner from a turret. Using a 2nd tower completely will net about 5-6 hits for 8 AP and 4 MP(Bridge Paola using front turrets), while the Pilot would get 3-4 hits for the same amount. I think normal damage(without projects) for Gunner is also higher and tends to oneshot standard/Aracks more often.
However, besides lenses, that have higher value for Pilots(60%72% for Gunner, 80%96%), turret improvements are scarce. Only faster recharge and double damage with a specific artifact are possible, while the 6th base(D7) is usually a must-have and there's a handful of projects improving the efficiency of Pilots with Blaster Gun considered one of the strongest projects overall.
For large amounts of hunters Pilots tend to be better as they don't have to move that much and have overall more charges.

On august 7, 2017
factoryman942

ok so:

  • Shooter gives free shots, so the most effective method per shot is the best candidate.
  • Turrets have base 2-4 damage and a 30% hit chance - this becomes 60% 4-8 damage with gunner.
    • 4-8 is an average damage of 6;
    • 60% x 6 is 3.6 damage/shot on average.
  • Patrollers do a base damage of 3-6, with an 80% hitchance as a pilot. 3-6 averages to 4.5.
    • 4.5 damage x 80% = 3.6 damage per shot too.
  • (It's also worth noting that patrollers will hit more, but with a lower average damage - 1/4 to kill a standard hunter; a turret with Gunner hits less, but with higher damage, with either 60% chance or 66.6% chance depending on how the double damage works)
  • However, Comms base D7 and the Blaster Guns project will increase the damage of patrollers by 1 each; this will raise the average to 5.5 (6.5 with both). This causes the Patroller's average damage/shot to go to 4.4 (and 5.2 with both upgrades). It will also raise the chance to kill a standard hunter to 50%, or 75% with both.



Conclusion: A Pilot with both BG and D7 base has a greater chance of oneshotting a regular Hunter than a Gunner, so if you have both, the Pilot will likely be more effective than the Gunner. If only one (or none) of these upgrades are possessed, the Gunner will likely be more effective, especially if the Gunner is given priority on shooting normal Hunters and the Pilots are used for defence against asteroids, Trax, etc.

Q59 Also, do stacked pills have different effect when consumed, or all stack will have the same effect on you and you able to test it without needed skills?
On august 18, 2017
iamp

Stacked pills do have the same effect, but the effect is different per ship. For example:
On ship 1: Pinq pill gives 2 morale and cures Migraine, so for EVERY single Pinq on the ship (including future pills from Narcotics Distiller), it will have that effect.

How do i check whether a person is taking a hunger damage on my ship?? I want to do this before trading the inactive person. If he is mush, i would like to keep the body instead of trading.
On november 30, 2017
Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mÃ©chant ?

When you are in the same room, you can see the person blink red at cycle change, which means they're taking damage. If there is no external cause (like a roomshake, a steel plate, a fire or an electrical spike), it means that the person is starving or ill.

You can also check if they have full hp, heal them if they're not, and check again the next cycle to see if they have taken hunger damage.

Just remember that people are hungry 3 days after they start the ship (D4C4 for someone who woke up on D1C4) and start taking damage the next cycle. If they already have eaten, it takes a little longer (D4C8 if they ate a ration on D1C4, D4C5 for a banana...). Players who start the tutorial but stay in the lab start starving immediately.

On december 9, 2017
Enigma

A81: 0 morale due to day change should kill you everytime, however it's all dependent on the event order when it comes to fatal depression.

Day change morale loss events happen first, and so if they reduce you to 0, then you will die as they happen before the 0 morale check is made for fatal depression. However if they don't reduce you to 0, for example to 1, and THEN you have a panic attack, or a crew member starves then you will not die until the following cycle change despite being reduced to 0 over the cycle change, as that is when the fatal depression check is made.

Disclaimer: This is my personal understanding, I do not know the code.

Franfran2424
factoryman942
  • Shooter gives free shots, so the most effective method per shot is the best candidate.
  • Turrets have base 2-4 damage and a 30% hit chance - this becomes 60% 4-8 damage with gunner.
  • 4-8 is an average damage of 6;
  • 60% x 6 is 3.6 damage/shot on average.
  • Patrollers do a base damage of 3-6, with an 80% hitchance as a pilot. 3-6 averages to 4.5.
  • 4.5 damage x 80% = 3.6 damage per shot too.
  • (It's also worth noting that patrollers will hit more, but with a lower average damage - 1/4 to kill a standard hunter; a turret with Gunner hits less, but with higher damage, with either 60% chance or 66.6% chance depending on how the double damage works)
  • However, Comms base D7 and the Blaster Guns project will increase the damage of patrollers by 1 each; this will raise the average to 5.5 (6.5 with both). This causes the Patroller's average damage/shot to go to 4.4 (and 5.2 with both upgrades). It will also raise the chance to kill a standard hunter to 50%, or 75% with both.

Checking old threads.

Average base accuracy with gunner is not 60%, because failed shots increase next shot accuracy. Running a python simulation 1M times, the actual long term average accuracy is around 69% (0.5% error margin).
Average accuracy as a pilot is 82.5% (using same simulation method, getting a similar error margin).

This means that the average damage per shot fired would be 4.14 for gunners and 3.71 for pilots, assuming the given numbers for damage on the old post are OK.
-But as was said on the original thread, due to these damage ranges, pilots on patrollers do 6 damage only 25% of the times they hit, often needing a second shot to finish hunters.
Gunner users would do 6 damage (or more) 60% of the times they hit, being quite more lethal on average.

  • What does this mean in numbers of destroyed hunters, then?
    A pilot would down 41.25 hunters per 100 shots (with 82.5 hits), while a gunner would destroy 51.67 hunters for 100 shots (with 69 hits).

Now let's assume optimal conditions for both (2 lenses, the neron project and base that increase patroller damage, and invertebrate shell).

  • Gunners would have a 73.9% accuracy, and pilots a 95.2% (which makes no sense, should be over 96% always, but the code I used is correct, so I might need to check again later or python random.randint code is broken)
  • This translates into pilots killing 79.3 hunters with 100 shots, and gunners killing 73.9 hunters per 100 shots.

TO SUM UP: a gunner is better if the pilots receive no upgrades, but with full upgrades, pilots vastly outclass gunners (more ease to fire many times instead of moving between cannons, more average damage...)

Code used.
